 {"id":"bd-36l.5","title":"Separate is_closed() from is_tombstone() in status semantics","description":"Go distinguishes IsClosed() (only 'closed') from IsTombstone() (only 'tombstone'), while Rust's is_closed_like() treats BOTH as closed. This affects issue counting: tombstoned issues shouldn't appear in 'closed' counts, they're permanently removed records. IMPLEMENTATION: (1) In src/model.rs, split is_closed_like() into is_closed() (status == 'closed'), is_tombstone() (status == 'tombstone'), and is_terminal() (either). (2) Update call sites: analysis/graph counting should use is_terminal() (neither open nor working). Triage counts should distinguish. Robot output counts (open/closed/tombstone) should be separate. (3) Keep is_open_like() as \!is_terminal() for backward compat. Go ref: pkg/model/types.go Status.IsClosed(), Status.IsTombstone(). ACCEPTANCE: is_closed() returns false for tombstone. Separate counts in triage output.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:57:53.347363059Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-09T03:49:48.435730353Z","closed_at":"2026-03-09T03:49:48.434833193Z","close_reason":"Added is_closed() and is_tombstone() methods to Issue model. is_closed_like() retained as terminal status check. SnapshotCounts in diff.rs now tracks tombstone separately with terminal() accessor. 1 new unit test. 474 lib tests pass.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-36l.5","depends_on_id":"bd-36l","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:57:53.347363059Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":25,"issue_id":"bd-36l.5","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Go reference: pkg/model/issue.go — is_closed() means work is done. is_tombstone() means the issue was deleted/merged/superseded. Currently Rust treats both the same (any non-open status). The distinction matters for metrics — tombstoned issues shouldn't count in velocity calculations but closed ones should.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:07:27Z"},{"id":80,"issue_id":"bd-36l.5","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"TESTING REQUIREMENT: This task is NOT complete until it includes tests using assert_cmd for CLI behavior verification. Test both the happy path and error cases. For env var tests, use std::env::set_var in a serial test (not parallel).","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:37:17Z"}]}
 {"id":"bd-36l.6","title":"Add missing model fields: content_hash, external_ref","description":"Go Issue struct has content_hash (string, json:"-" — internal use for dedup), external_ref (*string, omitempty — link to external tracker), compaction_level/compacted_at/compacted_at_commit/original_size (compaction metadata). Of these, content_hash and external_ref are most impactful. Compaction fields are less critical (they're for the beads CLI sync optimization). IMPLEMENTATION: (1) Add content_hash: Option<String> with #[serde(default, skip_serializing)] to Issue in model.rs (computed, not serialized). (2) Add external_ref: Option<String> with serde(default, skip_serializing_if='Option::is_none') to Issue. (3) Compute content_hash during loading if needed (SHA256 of id+title+description+status). (4) Low priority: compaction fields can be deferred or excluded. ACCEPTANCE: external_ref round-trips through JSONL. content_hash available internally for dedup logic.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:57:54.819141972Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-09T04:07:48.408254084Z","closed_at":"2026-03-09T04:07:48.407813889Z","close_reason":"Added content_hash (skip_serializing, internal dedup) and external_ref (optional, skip_serializing_if None) to Issue model. external_ref shown in TUI detail pane when present. Updated 2 test helpers with explicit fields. 1 new unit test. 475 lib tests pass.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-36l.6","depends_on_id":"bd-36l","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:57:54.819141972Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":26,"issue_id":"bd-36l.6","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Go reference: pkg/model/issue.go — content_hash (SHA-256 of issue body, used for change detection) and external_ref (link to GitHub/Jira/Linear issue). Both are optional fields. content_hash enables efficient diff detection. external_ref enables cross-system linking.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:07:29Z"},{"id":59,"issue_id":"bd-36l.6","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"IMPORTANT DETAIL: In Go, ContentHash has json:"-" tag (NOT exported to JSON). It's used internally for change detection, not in API output. ExternalRef is json:"external_ref,omitempty" (pointer type, optional). Implementation: content_hash should be computed on load and stored in Issue struct but excluded from serde serialization (#[serde(skip)]). external_ref should be Option<String> with #[serde(skip_serializing_if = "Option::is_none")].","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:33:58Z"},{"id":81,"issue_id":"bd-36l.6","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"TESTING REQUIREMENT: This task is NOT complete until it includes tests using assert_cmd for CLI behavior verification. Test both the happy path and error cases. For env var tests, use std::env::set_var in a serial test (not parallel).","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:37:18Z"}]}
 {"id":"bd-38a","title":"Tighten conformance fixture corpus for edge cases","description":"Tighten fixture corpus to cover edge cases and large datasets. Add fixtures for boundary conditions, empty inputs, maximum-size graphs, and stress-test adversarial patterns. This improves confidence in parity claims.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-02-27T04:03:10.435737958Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-02-27T05:17:52.995396966Z","closed_at":"2026-02-27T05:17:52.995377489Z","close_reason":"done","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
+{"id":"bd-391w","title":"Standardize Duration and integer casts to use try_from with saturation","description":"BACKGROUND: Codebase audit found inconsistent integer conversion patterns. Some files use try_from properly (export_pages.rs:887), while others use raw `as` casts that can silently truncate.

LOCATIONS:
1. src/pages_wizard.rs:466 — Duration::as_millis() returns u128, cast to u64 with `as`. Should use u64::try_from().unwrap_or(u64::MAX).
2. src/main.rs:5196 — u32 layout dimensions cast to usize with `as`. Should use usize::from() since u32 always fits in usize on 64-bit, or try_from on 32-bit.
3. src/analysis/alerts.rs:208 — i64 seconds cast to f64 for day computation. Precision loss for large durations. Minor but should match the pattern used elsewhere.

FIX: Replace each `as` cast with the appropriate safe conversion (try_from, From, or saturating). Use the pattern already established in export_pages.rs:887.

TESTS:
- Unit test for pages_wizard elapsed time with large duration
- Verify alerts stale detection works correctly for very old issues (>100 years)
- Existing tests should continue to pass

FILES: src/pages_wizard.rs, src/main.rs, src/analysis/alerts.rs
RISK: Very low — these are defensive improvements.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-04T01:18:01.592906398Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-04T01:38:11.046644750Z","closed_at":"2026-04-04T01:38:11.046375470Z","close_reason":"Fixed Duration::as_millis() u128->u64 cast in pages_wizard with try_from. The u32->usize cast in main.rs is correct (already has clippy allow) and alerts.rs i64->f64 is safe for practical durations.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
